<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-074-630  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 074 630.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>T H E Journal (Technological Horizons In Education)  Nov 1989 v17n4 p64(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The learning business: corporate thinking and school systemcomputing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cox, Clifford E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Chicago Public Schools' comprehensive student information(CSI) system was designed to improve student achievement, reducepaperwork, and help prevent dropouts.andP;  CSI was designed primarilyby former teachers, and was programmed from scratch using UnisysCorp's MAPPER fourth-generation language.andP;  CSI includes an onlinedatabase to facilitate tracking the school system's 400,000students.andP;  It also includes an electronic attendance application,flexible report generation capabilities, and grade reporting,medical, student scheduling, and special-education subsystems.andO;CSI is also growing into the area of finances, and staff usershave grown to about 3,000.andP;  The Chicago Public Schools wantcomputers to become tools to facilitate student learning, andtheir 600 school libraries are currently being automated.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CitiesComputer SystemsSystem DesignManagement of EDPEducationEducational AdministrationApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>